SIMPLE: nor
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nor
<hw>Nor</hw> <pr>(n⟦ocir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>conj.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>nor</ets>, contr. from <ets>nother</ets>. See
<er>Neither</er>.]</ety> <def>A negative connective or particle,
introducing the second member or clause of a negative proposition,
following <xex>neither</xex>, or <xex>not</xex>, in the first member or
clause (as <xex>or</xex> in affirmative propositions follows
<xex>either</xex>). <xex>Nor</xex> is also used sometimes in the first
member for <xex>neither</xex>, and sometimes the <xex>neither</xex> is
omitted and implied by the use of <xex>nor</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Provide neither gold <qex>nor</qex> silver, <qex>nor</qex> brass,
in your purses, <qex>nor</qex> scrip for your journey.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. x. 9, 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where neither moth <qex>nor</qex> rust doth corrupt.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. vi. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I love him not, <qex>nor</qex> fear him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where neither party is <qex>nor</qex> true, <qex>nor</qex>
kind.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Simois <qex>nor</qex> Xanthus shall be wanting there.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>noradrenaline</ent>⟦br⟧
